Date: 27/12/1935
Source: Evening Post
Author:
Vol / Page: 6
Edition:
Quote: A river-ford death already figures in the holiday casualties.  The fords of rivers generally claim a strong, efficient type of victim, because other types usually do not take a risk at an obviously tricky ford; but it was different in the roadless, bridgeless days, when all backblockers had to choose between the ford or remaining in the wilderness, and it was then that drowning in a river became known as "the New Zealand death."
